Search for declarations of type by simple name searches for "name*".

Steps:
- have a project with a 5.0 JDK in workspace
- Search > Java..., search for type declarations with name "State" (including JRE)

=> Search results not only contain matches like java.lang.Thread.State, but also java.sql.Statement, etc.

The problem is in JDT/UI's SearchUtils.isCamelCasePattern(String):
	public static boolean isCamelCasePattern(String pattern) {
		return SearchPattern.validateMatchRule(
			pattern, 
			SearchPattern.R_CAMELCASE_MATCH
			) == SearchPattern.R_CAMELCASE_MATCH;
	}

This returns true for strings like "State", and camel case search is always a prefix search. I'm not sure about the right way to resolve the problem, but I think the user should have the possibility to do an "exact" search for all possible type names.

We should either disable camel case search in the Java Search dialog or give the user explicit control over the match rule, e.g. by replacing the "Case sensitive" checkbox by a Combo with "Case sensitive", "Case insensitive", "Camel Case", and (soon;-) "Regular Expression". The glob pattern help for * and ? should then only be shown for the "Case (in)sensitive" rules.

Not sure if this is intended. Either way, I'm not a fan of it ;) 

public static boolean isSupportedModule(IModuleType[] moduleTypes, String typeId, String versionId) {
	if (moduleTypes != null) {
		int size = moduleTypes.length;
		for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
			if (isSupportedModule(moduleTypes[i], typeId,versionId))
				return true;
		}
	}
	return false;
}

Case is as follows:
   moduleTypes = new ModuleType[] { };  // empty
   typeId = "";
   versionId = "";
returning false

The reason I don't like it:
   First programatically I don't like it. If someone passes in that they support 5 modules, but typeId is still "" and versionId is still "", isSupportedModule will return true (because isSupportedModule calls matches(String a, String b), and one of the tests is a.startsWith(b), and since b = "", a always starts with b.)   Thus, so long as the runtime claims to support ANY moduletype (even assuming the module type doesnt exist), the method returns true, while the runtime that supports the empty array returns false.

   My example:
     I'm trying to add a runtime type to be used in projects, almost as a simple classpath provider, so that when a user creates a new dynamic web project, and selects the runtime, they can select this simple shell of a runtime. In my plugin.xml, my runtime (aka simple classpath container) supports no modules as it's just a bunch of jars. 

When selecting the 'new...' button from the runtime section of the New Dynamic Web project wizard, the resulting window's viewer defaults to sorting all runtime types by vendor. My runtime is not included only because it fails the isSupportedModule(etc...) check, even though its asking whether the empty string is supported. 

My suggestion:
   if (moduleTypes != null) {
	int size = moduleTypes.length;

        // FIX SUGGESTION
        if( size == 0 && typeId.equals("")) return true;
        // END FIX SUGGESTION 

	for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
		if (isSupportedModule(moduleTypes[i], typeId,versionId))
			return true;
	}
   }
   return false;

In FormWizardPage, you used 'parent()' to set the wizard page control. This is wrong because the form widget is the real child of the page parent. You should call 'setControl(_theForm)' instead.

	public void createControl(final Composite parent) {
		_formToolkit = new FormToolkit(parent.getDisplay());

		_theForm = toolkit().createForm(parent); 

		finishCreateControl(); 
		setControl(_theForm); 
	}

