	shell.setSize(shell.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT, SWT.DEFAULT));

The problem is that you are resizing the Shell during the createControl() of one of the pages, and this appears to be confusing the WizardDialog. I have tried stripping all forms and it still fails to show the second page if you resize the Shell:

// set the shell to its preferred size to prevent gigantic wizard
final Shell shell = getShell(); 
shell.setSize(shell.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT, SWT.DEFAULT)); 

While this is probably bad style - the wizard asked you to create the page and you are adjusting the Shell - there are no restrictions documented in the API, so this is either a bug in the wizard dialog or an undocumented restriction. Sending to UI for comment.

On PageOne if you remove the line:
	Shell.setSize(shell.computeSize(SWT.DEFAULT, SWT.DEFAULT)); 
the wizard will size the dialog correctly for you.  Also, in PageTwo#createControl add the following line after creating the composite:
	myOwn.setLayout(new FormLayout());	
to get the button to appear without resizing.

If you want to set your own size for the wizard, use WizardDialog#setPageSize or WizardDialog##setMinimumPageSize in the constructor of your wizard class (ResizableWizardDialog).

In constructing the helper for a container displayed in the JavaBean view, the helper is set with a VisualContainerPolicy having a null value for the container object.  A valid container object is later explicitly set to the container policy, but merely as a side-effect to the helper.  Initialization of the helper is not possible where initialization depends on a valid identification of the container that the helper supports.

The current actual series of operations are:

// in ContainerTreeEditPart.createEditPolicies() 
treeContainerPolicy = new TreeVisualContainerEditPolicy(getContainerPolicy()); 

// in ContainerTreeEditPart.createLayouPolicyHelper() 
lpHelper = BeanAwtUtilities.getLayoutPolicyFactoryFromLayoutManager 
      (layoutManager,EditDomain.getEditDomain( this ))
          .getLayoutPolicyHelper( null );
treeContainerPolicy .setPolicyHelper(lpHelper); 

// in TreeVisualContainerEditPolicy.setPolicyHelper() 
// -- here the policy has a null value for the container --
helper.setContainerPolicy((VisualContainerPolicy) containerPolicy);

// in TreeVisualContainerEditpolicy.activate() 
containerPolicy .setContainer(getHost().getModel()); 

The problem is with the order of the last two lines.

The simplest fix appears to be to add an explicit helper.setContainerPolicy( containerPolicy) call immediately after containerPolicy .setContainer(getHost().getModel()) in TreeVisualContainerEditpolicy.activate(). 

This will make explicit the setting of the container (and detectable through overrides of helper#setContainerPolicy).

(If the view is rewritten at some time in the future, perhaps the better fix would be to originally call BeanAwtUtilities.getLayoutPolicyFactoryFromLayoutManager with a complete policy object rather than null.)

If an annotation processor adds a warning, such as via this code,

   messager.printWarning(mirror.getPosition(), message + annoValue.getValue());

all quick fix options loaded from clicking in the gutter disappear.  They are still available from the problems view.  Note that it's not just quick fixes from the particular annotation processor (or annotation processors in general), but all quick fixes for any error/warning (unimported type, missing field declaration, etc).

Marking report as a duplicate.  The only workaround I can think of, which is a bit crazy, is to use a one-item table.  See snippet below:

public static void main(String [] args) {
	Display display = new Display();
	Shell shell = new Shell(display);
	shell.setBounds(10,10,200,200);
	shell.setLayout(new GridLayout());
	new Button(shell, SWT.CHECK).setText("normal button 1");
	Table table = new Table(shell, SWT.CHECK);
	table.setBackground(shell.getBackground());
	TableItem item = new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE);
	item.setText("gray");
	item.setGrayed(true);
	new Button(shell, SWT.CHECK).setText("normal button 2");
	shell.open();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch()) display.sleep();
	}
	display.dispose();
}


